Ask HN: Don’t Feel Like I Fit In, Should I Complete My Degree?
text:
I’m two quarters away from either a CS or a pure math degree. I feel I don’t fit in inside professional environments. I’m currently self employed and make enough to pay my rent and live decently. I like being self employed but have enough free time to pursue a real career, without sacrificing my self employment income. I enjoy problem solving and don’t program on my own at all usually but when I get immersed in a problem I really feel ‘in the zone’, and I love that, and I love that programming is all about that. But to be clear I’m not one of the types that just does this stuff in his free time regularly. When I have a problem to solve that involves programming I love it. I love the flexibility in design and the impermanence of solutions, the infinite pursuit of the optimal form. I enjoy refactoring for example, but I’m just a n00b.

I really want a WFH job to couple with my own work, which also takes place at home. I’m sorry to make “one of these” threads but I don’t know any better group to ask. I’m trying to read books on self-esteem and stuff to fit in better and be on campus more too. I got a job for the quasi-government recently (USPS) just to get out of the house and I’m feeling the same way, like I don’t belong. To be honest, I want to be a good programmer but if it’s not a good fit I should pivot.

title: Ask HN: What to do when your side project is losing steam in a nascent space
text:
I have a looney project I worked on for my tradesman degree in Computer Science. This was 4 years ago and I never thought it would get its legs.

Fast forward 4 years, I say I chalked up my initial gusto as irrational exuberance. But eerily, when I now look at the base of similar companies it's like 2-3 that are in my space whereas previously there were 0-1.

What should I do? I feel pressured to keep iterating regardless of cost. Any help would be appreciated. I want to resurrect my ancient code and get it known out there.

The competition has better angels, better execution but not better ideas (I think my idea is revolutionary).

Dear HN: Should I just throw in the towel on this wacky idea?

title: Help: Google Chrome UX Downgrade
text:
This is my fault for still using Chrome.

Today it auto-updated itself to the latest version (110), and in dark mode (windows 10) on the url bar, when typing things into the urlbar, it no longer shows a blinking cursor if I type in anything resembling previous sites.

To wit: https://i.imgur.com/1r15aY3.png <- this is what it looks like. No blinking cursor, no contrast whatsoever between what I've typed, and what is being auto-completed.

How do I turn this off? And more generally, how do I just... make.... auto-updating stop?
